Title : Lou Lewis
Text : '''Lou Lewis''' (died 11 January 2010, aged 71) was trade unionist in [[London]].
<ref>[http://ucatt.infobo.co.uk/files/buildingworker/Building-Worker-2010-Spring.pdf" UCATT - Building Worker -Spring 2010]</ref>

Lewis was born in Liverpool and joined the [[Amalgamated Society of Woodworkers]] (ASW) at the start of his carpentery apprenticeship.<ref name=Barbican>{{cite book|last1=Wall|first1=Christine|last2=Clarke|first2=Linda|last3=McGuire|first3=Charlie|last4=Muñoz-Rojas|first4=Olivia|title=Building the Barbican 1962 – 1982: taking the industry out of the dark ages|year=2012|publisher=University of Westminster|location=London|isbn=978-0-903109-34-5|url=http://www.buildingworkersstories.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/BarbicanPamphlet.pdf}}</ref>

He was the union convener at the [[Barbican Estate|Barbican]] site in central London, where he led several so-called [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat disputes]] and a lengthy strike in 1967.<ref name="construction.co.uk">[http://www.construction.co.uk/construction_news.asp?newsid=105243 Construction.co.uk]</ref> He was organiser of the London Joint SItes Committee which brought together building workers across London.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tilley|first=John|title=This Smiling Man|journal=Daily Mail|date=22 February 1967}}</ref>

Lewis was a founder member [[Building Workers’ Charter]] movement which was active in opposing the [[Lump Labour Scheme]].<ref name="grahamstevenson">[http://www.grahamstevenson.me.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=912 www.grahamstevenson.me.uk]</ref><ref>[https://www.marxists.org/history/etol/newspape/isj/1975/no075/goulding.htm International Socialism, No.75, February 1975, pp.22-27.]</ref><ref name="workerspower">[http://www.workerspower.co.uk/2011/11/building-workers-the-great-strike-of-1972/ Building workers: The great strike of 1972]</ref>

Later, the [[Amalgamated Society of Woodworkers]] (ASW) joined the AUBTW to form the [[Amalgamated Society of Woodworkers, Painters and Builders]] (ASWPB), and in December 1971, the name was changed to the [[Union of Construction, Allied Trades and Technicians]] (UCATT). Lewis became UCATT Regional Secretary for the London South East Region, and he was a member of the Communist Party’s Executive Committee (during the 70s and onwards).<ref name="grahamstevenson" />

